sys_update_xml.name: content_block_0f88dc214f6f1300932c01bda310c73f
sys_update_xml.payload:
truegeneralfalsefalseintegration recommendFor inbound integrations or web services, the Best Practice to ensure security is to configure integration only accounts. In addition to providing an extra layer of security, separating integrations into different accounts also makes debugging more efficient.

Review the listed accounts. Ensure that each inbound / outbound integration is listed and if not, consider adding an integration or web services only account for that integration. If any appear to be a personal account, validate the owner and functions and consider creating new web service / integration accounts.

]]>content_block_staticadmin2018-07-26 15:47:120f88dc214f6f1300932c01bda310c73f0integration recommendglobalglobalcontent_block_static_0f88dc214f6f1300932c01bda310c73fadmin2018-07-26 15:47:12

sys_update_xml.name: content_block_85e4e31d4fab1300932c01bda310c734
sys_update_xml.payload:
truegeneralfalsefalseres code recommendResolution code is a choice field that is normally required when an Incident is Resolved or Closed. It is a powerful data point and can be used to assess the efficiency of the Incident process while also providing data segmentation from costly, in person resolution vs. low cost remote assistance. 

Common causes of missing Resolution codes include use of the Cancel feature, updates to Incidents by customized processes and inbound integrations. Validate the different ways in which Incidents are made inactive in your system and ensure all data fields are accurately entered. Consider adding Resolution codes of 'Canceled' and 'Canceled - Request created' for consistency.

]]>content_block_staticadmin2018-07-26 12:17:2585e4e31d4fab1300932c01bda310c7340res code recommendglobalglobalcontent_block_static_85e4e31d4fab1300932c01bda310c734admin2018-07-26 12:17:25

sys_update_xml.name: content_block_058c04554fe31300932c01bda310c725
sys_update_xml.payload:
truegeneralfalsefalseinactive resolved"Resolved" is a system level date / time field automatically captured when an Incident is Resolved or Closed. It is normally set by the mark_resolved Business Rule. This field is critical to reporting as it represents when service was restored to the client and is also used out of the box by Performance Analytics to determine whether an Incident is open. 

The 2 most common causes of Incidents missing Resolved is use of the Canceled State, and inbound integrations which close Incidents but don't enter all the required fields. If Canceled is being used, ensure that Incident related Indicator Sources and Report Sources are updated. If the Incidents are related to an integration, update to the inbound integration to populate the Resolved field.

]]>content_block_staticadmin2018-07-25 20:26:32058c04554fe31300932c01bda310c7252inactive resolvedglobalglobalcontent_block_static_058c04554fe31300932c01bda310c725admin2018-07-26 12:20:27

sys_update_xml.name: content_block_6c2888dd4fa31300932c01bda310c7c3
sys_update_xml.payload:
truegeneralfalsefalseopen unassigned recommendWhile not required, it is Best Practice for an individual within the Assignment Group to take ownership of the Incident. This ensures clear accountability, makes it more efficient to stay on top of status, provides a clear point of contact for Caller communications, but also makes sure people get credit for the work they are doing. 

Evaluate the unassigned Incidents - it is normal for an Incident to be unassigned when it first hits a Group's Queue. Determine if there are certain Groups or areas where unassigned Incidents are more common. Communicate the importance and value of assigning Incidents to individuals to Group Managers.

]]>content_block_staticadmin2018-07-25 19:53:046c2888dd4fa31300932c01bda310c7c31open unassigned recommendglobalglobalcontent_block_static_6c2888dd4fa31300932c01bda310c7c3admin2018-07-25 19:58:00

sys_update_xml.name: content_block_47e55ced4f2f1300932c01bda310c70c
sys_update_xml.payload:
truegeneralfalsefalsesys admin recommendThis is the number of users in your system who have the 'admin' role. Anyone with this role can basically do anything in your system.

Verify that all admins are correct, preferably only people who have been certified by ServiceNow as System Administrators. Avoid giving this role to a broad number of people as it increases the risk of unapproved changes to the system. Ensure that each admin is configured to use an independent Update Set, and that someone is responsible to review Update Sets to ensure no unauthorized changes have been done.

 

]]>content_block_staticadmin2018-07-26 15:35:3347e55ced4f2f1300932c01bda310c70c0sys admin recommendglobalglobalcontent_block_static_47e55ced4f2f1300932c01bda310c70cadmin2018-07-26 15:35:33

sys_update_xml.name: content_block_ebe75ced4f2f1300932c01bda310c711
sys_update_xml.payload:
truegeneralfalsefalselicense recommend"itil" users are important as they represent a paid license from ServiceNow. This report gives you a basic data point to help maximize value by identifying holders of paid licenses that are not using the system.

Review the list of "itil" users who have not logged in in 6 months. Are they still with the organization? Did their job change? Do they still require access? Use this as an opportunity to reclaim licenses from dormant users in order to minimize waste in additional license purchases. 

]]>content_block_staticadmin2018-07-26 15:42:40ebe75ced4f2f1300932c01bda310c7110license recommendglobalglobalcontent_block_static_ebe75ced4f2f1300932c01bda310c711admin2018-07-26 15:42:40

sys_update_xml.name: content_block_aaf1445d4fa31300932c01bda310c7e9
sys_update_xml.payload:
truegeneralfalsefalseRecommendations 1While it is more common for an Incident to be open for an extended time, not updating an Incident for more than 6 months is a clear indication of a process issue. This may be because no one is working on it, or that the work has been completed but no one has updated the Incident to Resolved. Other common causes include:

  1. "Lost" tickets that have fallen through the cracks
  2. Groups who have stopped managing their ServiceNow queues
  3. Overuse of the 'On hold' State
  4. Process mis-use, e.g. using Incidents for RFCs, or Requests
  5. Integrations - Incidents created by an integration or alert process, which are never closed

Review each Incident to determine if there is a valid reason for it to remain open. Contact the Assignee or Group Manager to raise awareness and determine an action plan if necessary. A useful Best Practice is to ensure every Incident has an Assigned to, so ownership and responsibility are clear.

]]>content_block_staticadmin2018-07-25 19:29:46aaf1445d4fa31300932c01bda310c7e90Recommendations 1globalglobalcontent_block_static_aaf1445d4fa31300932c01bda310c7e9admin2018-07-25 19:29:46

sys_update_xml.name: content_block_ac2d957d4f231300932c01bda310c732
sys_update_xml.payload:
truegeneralfalsefalselocation recommendLocation is the primary way in which the system recognizes geographically disperse workforces. It may be used to drive workflow, service level agreements, services entitlements or many other processes in ServiceNow.

Evaluate the users missing Locations. Many may be service or integration accounts. Compare this information to your Active Directory or other Directory Services application and if missing, fix it at the source. If the information in AD is correct, review your inbound LDAP integration transform maps for possible issues.

sys_update_xml.name: content_block_65cee7914feb1300932c01bda310c760
sys_update_xml.payload:
truegeneralfalsefalseinactive group recommendAs organizations grow and adapt, it is common to add new Groups and deactivate old Groups. However in some cases, the Incidents are not transitioned and remain in the queue of a deactivated Group. This results in situations where Incidents are not being worked as they do not appear in the Group queues of active Groups.

Review each Incident to determine if it is still an issue and when the last action was taken. Socialize the Incidents with the current Group managers to determine how it should be triaged. Reassign the Incidents to active Groups. 

]]>content_block_staticadmin2018-07-26 12:44:5265cee7914feb1300932c01bda310c7600inactive group recommendglobalglobalcontent_block_static_65cee7914feb1300932c01bda310c760admin2018-07-26 12:44:52

sys_update_xml.name: content_block_442b2fdd4fab1300932c01bda310c7a8
sys_update_xml.payload:
truegeneralfalsefalseopen inc recommendMany records in ServiceNow have a flag field called 'Active'. This is used to control access and visibility across the system. Users are typically made inactive when they leave a company or organization so that historical records are maintained.

If you have inactive Users against open Incidents, basically it is saying the Caller is no longer valid. Review each Incident to determine if additional actions are required. Avoid canceling these records unless it is confirmed the Incident is not impacting other Users. Update the Caller field on the Incident with an appropriate individual.

]]>content_block_staticadmin2018-07-26 12:29:35442b2fdd4fab1300932c01bda310c7a80open inc recommendglobalglobalcontent_block_static_442b2fdd4fab1300932c01bda310c7a8admin2018-07-26 12:29:35

sys_update_xml.name: content_block_d7022b994fab1300932c01bda310c718
sys_update_xml.payload:
truegeneralfalsefalseinc close recommendClosed is a system level date / time field that is automatically capture by the mark_closed Business Rule. This happens when:

  • when an Incident is Canceled
  • when the Close button is pressed on an Incident
  • when a Resolved Incident is automatically Closed by the system

When Closed is missing from an inactive Incident, it is not possible to determine when the last actions on the Incident were completed. This is seen most often on heavily customized systems or as a result of inbound integrations. Review the associated records and try to identify similarities that will point you to the cause and try to fix the issue at its source.

]]>content_block_staticadmin2018-07-26 11:49:11d7022b994fab1300932c01bda310c7182inc close recommendglobalglobalcontent_block_static_d7022b994fab1300932c01bda310c718admin2018-07-26 12:21:39

sys_update_xml.name: content_block_25391d3d4f231300932c01bda310c73b
sys_update_xml.payload:
truegeneralfalsefalseemail recommendEmail is the primary way ServiceNow notifies users including ticket assignment, status, approvals and also to do things like send out scheduled reports. If your users do not have emails, it may significantly impact their experience as a customer (e.g. not knowing status) or fulfiller (e.g. not knowing tickets are being assigned to you).

Review the Users with missing emails - some may be service or integration accounts so will not impact customers. For actual people, compare the ServiceNow entry with what exists in Active Directory. If AD is incomplete fix the data at its source and it will populate in ServiceNow during the next LDAP sync. It is not recommended to add this field in ServiceNow only as it may be overwritten by your integration.

]]>content_block_staticadmin2018-07-27 15:08:4625391d3d4f231300932c01bda310c73b1email recommendglobalglobalcontent_block_static_25391d3d4f231300932c01bda310c73badmin2018-07-27 15:09:18

sys_update_xml.name: content_block_a49df7894fa31300932c01bda310c719
sys_update_xml.payload:
truegeneralfalsefalseRecommendationsLong running Incidents may be due to a variety of factors including:

  1. "Lost" tickets that have fallen through the cracks
  2. Groups who have stopped managing their ServiceNow queues
  3. Overuse of the 'On hold' State
  4. Process mis-use, e.g. using Incidents for RFCs, or Requests
  5. Integrations - Incidents created by an integration or alert process, which are never closed

Review each Incident to determine if there is a valid reason for it to remain open. Contact the Assignee or Group Manager to raise awareness and determine an action plan if necessary.

 

]]>content_block_staticadmin2018-07-25 19:06:45a49df7894fa31300932c01bda310c7192Recommendationsglobalglobalcontent_block_static_a49df7894fa31300932c01bda310c719admin2018-07-25 19:21:37

sys_update_xml.payload:
truegeneralfalsefalseblankThe Caller field is a key data point. The system uses the Caller field to determine related info, such as the Caller Department or Caller Location. Out of the box, this should never happen but does occur in customized systems, or situations where there is an inbound integration. 

Check each Incident, and the Incident sources (e.g. created by email? integration? user?). Try to determine the underlying cause of the missing Caller field and resolve the issue by fixing it at its source.

sys_update_xml.name: content_block_c0dc6fdd4fab1300932c01bda310c73f
sys_update_xml.payload:
truegeneralfalsefalseasssignee inactive recommendJust as Callers may become inactive, individual members of Assignment Groups who work on Incidents may also leave an organization and their User record become inactive. If there are inactive Assignee's on Incidents it is likely that no one is addressing the customer's issue leading to a poor customer experience.

Review each Incident to validate if work is continuing. In most cases the Assignee may be changed to the Group Manager who should then triage the Incident and reassign it to the appropriate resource. If there are more than 2-3 cases it is important to review your employee offboarding processes to ensure all active work is being transitioned from resources when they leave the organization.

sys_update_xml.name: content_block_218ad93d4f231300932c01bda310c7e0
sys_update_xml.payload:
truegeneralfalsefalsedepartment recommendServiceNow is a relational database. An important aspect of this is that fields like Department and Location are not saved on each Incident, but instead based on the User (Caller) record. If Departments are missing, there is no way to view data organized by Department. It is not possible to answer questions like "Which Departments are using which services?" or "Which Departments have the highest IT cost?"

As with other LDAP / AD populated fields, this should be fixed in your Active Directory or other Directory services application. 

]]>content_block_staticadmin2018-07-27 15:14:36218ad93d4f231300932c01bda310c7e00department recommendglobalglobalcontent_block_static_218ad93d4f231300932c01bda310c7e0admin2018-07-27 15:14:36

sys_update_xml.name: content_block_96cdd5fd4f231300932c01bda310c785
sys_update_xml.payload:
truegeneralfalsefalsename recommendNames do not drive workflow, however the ability to identify staff by name is a key component of having a quality user experience. 

Evaluate the Users who are missing a First or Last Name. Many may be service or integration accounts from Active Directory or other Directory Services application. Compare the records in ServiceNow to the AD source and if missing in AD, update it in AD. It is not recommended to update this in ServiceNow as it may be copied over during a future sync. If the records are accurate in AD, review your inbound LDAP integration transform maps for completeness. 

]]>content_block_staticadmin2018-07-27 15:26:3096cdd5fd4f231300932c01bda310c7850name recommendglobalglobalcontent_block_static_96cdd5fd4f231300932c01bda310c785admin2018-07-27 15:26:30

sys_update_xml.name: content_block_0755c8dd4fa31300932c01bda310c79b
sys_update_xml.payload:
truegeneralfalsefalseCat RecommendCategories provide a high level designation which is useful for organizations when looking at capacity, efficiency and consumption of the Incident process. This is critical to basic analysis of your Incident Process.

Missing Categories may be caused by a number of factors including poorly configured integrations or changes to the Categorization Structure (removing a Category). 

Examine the Incidents to look for a common source of the issue and fix it at its source. If Categorization has changed, determine a "From --> To" mapping to ensure the efficacy of reports and metrics for historical records.

]]>content_block_staticadmin2018-07-25 19:44:570755c8dd4fa31300932c01bda310c79b1Cat Recommendglobalglobalcontent_block_static_0755c8dd4fa31300932c01bda310c79badmin2018-07-25 19:45:44

sys_update_xml.name: content_block_600794214f6f1300932c01bda310c787
sys_update_xml.payload:
truegeneralfalsefalseitil user recommendSince their founding, ServiceNow has used the role 'itil' to denote fulfiller (people who actually work tickets) access to the system. All members of Assignment Groups typically have the 'itil' role and this corresponds to the number of ITSM licenses purchased from ServiceNow.

This number should roughly correspond to the number of staff in your IT Department. If the number seems high or low, review the list of users to ensure that everyone has the access that they need. 

]]>content_block_staticadmin2018-07-26 15:40:00600794214f6f1300932c01bda310c7870itil user recommendglobalglobalcontent_block_static_600794214f6f1300932c01bda310c787admin2018-07-26 15:40:00

sys_update_xml.name: content_block_11c498ed4f2f1300932c01bda310c75b
sys_update_xml.payload:
truegeneralfalsefalseactive user recommendThis is the total number of active Users, which typically will align with the total number of employees in the organization, including contractors and temporary staff. It is usually populated by an LDAP integration from your Active Directory instance.

Validate that the Users are actual people - service accounts, test accounts and other accounts that are not people should be excluded by updating the filters, OUs and other conditions in the LDAP integration. 

]]>content_block_staticadmin2018-07-26 15:26:3411c498ed4f2f1300932c01bda310c75b1active user recommendglobalglobalcontent_block_static_11c498ed4f2f1300932c01bda310c75badmin2018-07-26 15:31:19

sys_update_xml.name: content_block_90cbd93d4f231300932c01bda310c7e4
sys_update_xml.payload:
truegeneralfalsefalsemanager recommendThe most common use of 'Manager' is to determine approvals for IT service requests. It is also very valuable in analytics, as it enables 'rolling up' data by Manager to all levels of the organization.

Out of the box, the ServiceNow LDAP integration should pull Manager details from Active Directory and populate this field. Validate the information in Active Directory and if missing, add the information to AD. If AD is correct, review your inbound LDAP transform map to debug the issue.

sys_update_xml.name: content_block_02b688114fe31300932c01bda310c73c
sys_update_xml.payload:
truegeneralfalsefalseAssign RecommendOut of the box, the Assignment Group is not required, but if left empty should be automatically entered by the system using the Assignment Rules. More information is available here:

https://docs.servicenow.com/bundle/kingston-platform-administration/page/administer/task-table/concept/c_AssignmentRulesModule.html

Incidents with no Assignment Group may be caused by integrations, or errors in the Assignment Rules or other factors. Regardless it is a big deal - the Incidents will not appear in any Group queues and so are likely to be ignored resulting in a poor customer experience. Investigate each Incident to determine the appropriate Group, and then perform a "warm handover" to ensure clear accountability. 

]]>content_block_staticadmin2018-07-25 19:51:0802b688114fe31300932c01bda310c73c0Assign Recommendglobalglobalcontent_block_static_02b688114fe31300932c01bda310c73cadmin2018-07-25 19:51:08

truegeneralfalsefalseCaller topCallers on Incidents are held in the sys_user table and typically populated by a LDAP integration. This information is critical to an efficiently running instance and are used for everything from knowing who to email for approval to identifying service consumption across the user base. Having incomplete or inaccurate Caller data reduces the capabilities and value of every process and application in ServiceNow.
